	<div id="comment_top_64358502" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64358502" name="comment_link_64358502" href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23274804&amp;cid=64358502" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64358502)" >Re:$1 fee (more like $3-$5 to cover CC fees)</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64358502" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64358502); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~PsychoSlashDot">PsychoSlashDot</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~PsychoSlashDot">( 207849 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64358502">		
		on Sunday March 31, 2024 @08:57AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23274804&amp;cid=64358502">#64358502</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64358502"><p><div class="quote"><p>isolating Timmy from the world, which would do him significantly more harm than the "smut" ever would.</p></div><p>That leads to another point: Internet porn has been around for literally 35+ years.  So... where are all the peer-reviewed studies about screwed-up 45-year-olds, scarred by the things they were exposed to at 10?<br> <br>
Want to ban lead in gasoline?  You do some tests, and demonstrate that it causes brain damage.  Want to enforce motorcycle helmet laws?  You do some tests, and demonstrate that helmets reduce brain damage.  Want to pass massively privacy-invading, freedom-cramping legislation in the name of "the children"?  You need to do some tests and show that Internet porn does actual, quantifiable, measurable, demonstrable harm to children.<br> <br>
Bonus... I personally suspect that access just <i>helps</i> us to learn about ourselves as we grow up.  All I mean by this is that as a young adult when I first encountered porn, I pretty quickly realized what I liked and what I didn't like.  It didn't make me like things I wasn't going to like regardless.  I learned what acts I was interested in (at least watching, not necessarily doing), and what was revolting.  When it eventually came time to have a partner, I was better equipped to enjoy the bedroom, and more confident that asking for what I like wasn't absurd because... well... if there's a whole section on every site dedicated to <i>whatever</i>, maybe I shouldn't be ashamed because I'm not alone.<br> <br>
I'm straight and don't have any fringe kinks.  I can only imagine how isolated a porn-less teen who is unsure about their orientation or maybe has thoughts about hot candle wax and struggles with it all must feel.  Yes, we somehow survived for thousands of years before Internet porn, but... we also used to have massive hangups about gay people and ankles and... you get the point.  Maybe we're better off.  Maybe.  Perhaps some studies?</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64358502">
